4
00:00:18,670 --> 00:00:21,800
Now you’ve finished the first unit, you should be very familiar with this picture

5
00:00:21,800 --> 00:00:25,730
of the 4-layer model of the Internet. You now know that the Internet is broken down

6
00:00:25,730 --> 00:00:29,800
into four distinct layers, what the four layers are, and how they work together. But even

7
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:35,399
more importantly than how it works, you hopefully understand why it works this way and why layering

8
00:00:35,399 --> 00:00:38,530
is a good idea in all networks, not just the Internet.

9
00:00:38,530 --> 00:00:42,940
You’ve now seen that the Internet works by breaking data up into small units called

10
00:00:42,940 --> 00:00:47,840
packets. When you request a web page, your computer sends some packets to the web server.

11
00:00:47,840 --> 00:00:51,680
The Internet decides how these little pieces of data arrive to the right destination – and

12
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:55,780
how the packets the web server responds with, containing the page, make their way to you

13
00:00:55,780 --> 00:00:57,250
correctly as well.

14
00:00:57,250 --> 00:01:02,449
You‘ve learned how two architectural principles, layering and packets, come together, in the

15
00:01:02,449 --> 00:01:07,220
architectural principle of encapsulation. Encapsulation is how one takes layers and

16
00:01:07,220 --> 00:01:11,110
lets them use packets in a clean and simple way, such that each layer’s use of a packet

17
00:01:11,110 --> 00:01:15,280
is independent of the others. We’ll talk about a few more architectural principles

18
00:01:15,280 --> 00:01:20,850
