32
00:02:31,380 --> 00:02:37,030
4. Basic architectural ideas and principles. You’ve studied three fundamental principles

33
00:02:37,030 --> 00:02:41,390
of networks, all of which are very relevant to our understanding of the Internet. The

34
00:02:41,390 --> 00:02:46,160
first is packet switching, which is the simple way in which data is broken down into self-contained

35
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:50,000
packets of information that are forwarded hop-by-hop based on the information in the

36
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:56,140
packet header. The second is Layering, which we’ve already mentioned. And the third is

37
00:02:56,140 --> 00:03:01,530
encapsulation, which is the process of placing a packet processed at one layer inside the

38
00:03:01,530 --> 00:03:08,060
data of the packet below. This helps a clear separation of concerns between how data is

39
00:03:08,060 --> 00:03:12,210
processed at each layer in the hierarchy.

40
00:03:12,210 --> 00:03:16,170
you should now have a good understanding of the basic structure of the Internet and three

41
00:03:16,170 --> 00:03:20,470
basic architectural ideas. You understand how applications like your web browser works,

42
00:03:20,470 --> 00:03:23,720
and how the Internet delivers packets between two computers. You‘d probably heard the

43
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:29,230
term TCP/IP used before: now you know what TCP is and what IP is, and why they’re related.

44
00:03:29,230 --> 00:03:33,790
At first glance, these might seem like grungy, low-level details. But it turns out that they’re

45
00:03:33,790 --> 00:03:38,680
the bedrock of what the Internet is. Every year, new applications and uses of the Internet

46
00:03:38,680 --> 00:03:43,430
emerge. But all of them use these basic principles you’re learning about, and almost all of

47
00:03:43,430 --> 00:03:49,150
them use TCP/IP. By starting with these fundamentals that have remained amazingly constant, you’ll

48
00:03:49,150 --> 00:03:53,270
learn the knowledge that will continue to be important even as we move on to 5G wireless

49
00:03:53,270 --> 00:03:55,670
networks, Web 3.0, and the Internet of Things.

50
00:03:55,670 --> 00:04:00,790
And that’s part of what’s exciting. The Internet and what it can do is always expanding

51
00:04:00,790 --> 00:04:04,720
and changing. But there are some core ideas and principles which are constant through

52
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:10,810
all of that evolution. By learning them, you not only know how the Internet and networks

53
00:04:10,810 --> 00:04:14,819
work today, but most likely how they will work in 20 years as well.

